{"key":"post-9436172","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>9436172</id>\n<content>The q-tip test is bogus, because small pieces of bruised mycelium can rub off on the q-tip making the inexperienced eye think it's mold.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Bruising is bruising.&amp;nbsp; The analogy of bruising on your body carries over to mushrooms.&amp;nbsp; A bruised fruit or cake will have a blue or green color, but it's the &lt;i&gt;color of the tissue&lt;/i&gt;.&amp;nbsp;  If it's mold, it will look more like a scab from a wound on your body.&amp;nbsp; Mold spores will be on the &lt;b&gt;surface as a separate layer&lt;/b&gt;, just like a scab on your arm.&amp;nbsp; Another analogy is that mold spores often look like a layer of green sand on the surface of the fruit.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>9436329</next>\n<prev>9435766</prev>\n<first>9435304</first>\n<last>9436329</last>\n<when>1229366349</when>\n<utime>12/15/08 08:39 PM</utime>\n</post>"}